               <p>JOHN PERRING. I am a <rs id="t18241202-67-viclabel358" type="occupation">hatter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18241202-67-victim424 t18241202-67-viclabel358"></join>, and live at No. 413, Strand. On the 21st of November, about seven o'clock in<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182412020030"></xptr>the evening, I lost my handkerchief, between <placeName id="t18241202-67-crimeloc359">Windmill-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18241202-67-crimeloc359" type="placeName" value="Windmill-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18241202-67-crimeloc359" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18241202-67-off356 t18241202-67-crimeloc359"></join> and <placeName id="t18241202-67-crimeloc360">Panton-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18241202-67-crimeloc360" type="placeName" value="Panton-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18241202-67-crimeloc360" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18241202-67-off356 t18241202-67-crimeloc360"></join>. I had it in my hand a few minutes before, and I am sure it was safe in my pocket; it rained very fast. I had an umbrella in my left hand. I felt some one at my right-hand pocket. I turned round suddenly, and missed it, I saw the prisoner close upon me; he looked rather confused, and ran across the road to the opposite side of the way. I pursued him, and took hold of his collar; he was alone. I accused him of having taken it; he said, he had just picked one up; if it was mine I might have it. I then lifted up a blue apron which he had on, and discovered my handkerchief with my initials on it, and the mark of the Steam Washing Company; he resisted very much; but I got the assistance of a person, and took him to the watch-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18241202-67-person425">
